<h1>From Charles Carter</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sr</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Fredericksburgh June 5 1754</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>We had the agreable news of the victory obtaind by the Partie under your Command<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0064-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0064-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> I heartily congratulate you and all the Brave gentlen that were of the company. From this happy begining I am lead to hope you will soon make those cruel men know that numbers cant support an unrighteous cause God grant you may be blest with the like success and drive them Out of our Colony I had this affair in the begining much at heart and you are a witness to the share I had in promoting the Bill for defending our Frontiers and you may depend I shall be always ready to serve such brave men to the utmost of my power.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0064-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0064-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
<p>We are told the officers are very uneasy on acct of some late resolves of the Comittee I am not yet satisfied what their complaint is as it comes from a youth in the service I hope much may be imputd to his not being well informd[.]<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0064-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0064-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> While I was at the Committee I can aver there was the greatest readiness to promote and encourage the officers and men and make the most effectual provision no doubt any just complaint will meet with immediate redress for my part I shall always be a true friend to such deserving men I know the hardships you must suffer and I hope you will be amply rewarded and return crownd with Laurels. I should be glad to know the name of the unfortunate man that died in our Cause please to favour me with an Acct of every Important occurance and the grounds of the Complaint[.] You are so well satisfied of the importance of the trust reposd in you that it would be impertinence to use any Arguments to excite you to a courageous discharge of it My compliments to all the officers I am charm with their Bravery[.] I am Sr Yr most obligd hume Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Ch. Carter</p>
</div>
<div class="postscript">
<p>PS The above was wrote in the dark but I could not omit an opportunity to congratulate you on this happy occasion.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-01-02-pb-0129">[129]</span>
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0064-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>


   <p>Charles Carter (17071764), the third son of Robert (King) Carter, had his home at Cleve in King George County, on the left bank of the Rappahannock River below Fredericksburg and Ferry Farm, GWs boyhood home.</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0064-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0064-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-01-02-0052" class="document">Robert Dinwiddie to GW, 25 May 1754</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0064-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0064-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>Carter was chairman of the committee of the House of Burgesses that drew up the bill passed in Feb. 1754 to provide  10,000 for the campaign against the French and to create a committee, of which Carter was a member, to supervise the expenditure of the funds. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-01-02-0031&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-01-02-0031-fn-0009#GEWN-02-01-02-0031-fn-0009" class="document">Dinwiddie to GW, Jan. 1754, n.9</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-01-02-0064-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-01-02-0064-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>For the complaints of GW and his officers, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-01-02-0050" class="document">GW to Dinwiddie, second letter of 18 May 1754</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-01-02-0052" class="document">Dinwiddie to GW, 25 May 1754</a>.</p>

</div>
